      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "38776ec45eca1ab6",
      "text": "> Democracy and prosperity, a longer life, more equality and education: [[Capitalism]] has brought about many positive things. At the same time, however, it is ruining the climate and the environment, so that humanity's very existence is now at risk. \"Green growth\" is supposed to be the salvation, but economic expert and bestselling author Ulrike Herrmann holds against it: In her new book, she explains in an understandable and razor-sharp way why we need \"green shrinkage\" instead. The climate crisis is worsening daily, but in concrete terms almost nothing is changing. Greenhouse gases are increasing unchecked and dramatically. This failure is no accident, because the climate crisis aims at the heart of capitalism. Prosperity and growth are only possible by using technology and burning energy. Unfortunately, however, green energy from the sun and wind will never be enough to fuel global growth. So the industrialized countries must say goodbye to capitalism and strive for a circular economy in which only what can be recycled is consumed. But how to envision this green shrinkage? The best model is, of all things, the British wartime economy from 1940 onward. \"Herrmann's book is historically instructive and a good read. It points out where technological limitations to climate change lie. Yet it comes across as deterministic. Herrmann acknowledges that humans have solved many problems in the past. But she apparently doubts that this time it will be the same\" (deutschlandfunk.de). Ranked 9th on the nonfiction bestseller list for November 2022. Nominated for the longlist of the NDR Nonfiction Book Prize 2022.\n"
