      "text": "# [[Restructuring]] Behavioral Patterns "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7047046bb410de3b",
      "text": "Then it turned out that the way out of isolation was very difficult and paved with setbacks, since decades-old behavioral patterns and prejudices had to be dismantled and changed. A reduction in prejudices naturally corresponds to complicated learning processes that are also difficult to master personally, because restructuring behavioral patterns once they have become entrenched is always more difficult than practicing new patterns. Third, the discussions about whether this path should be taken at all and how quickly, as well as the successes and failures, had an intensifying effect on the internal party disputes.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "533bb7798f5d5967",
      "text": "* MCLAUGHLIN, BARRY, 1990. Restructuring. Applied Linguistics. 1 June 1990. Vol. 11, no. 2, p. 113–128. DOI 10.1093/applin/11.2.113. \n> This paper argues for a cognitive psychological approach to second language phenomena that emphasizes the importance of the development of automaticity and the process of restructuring. It is argued that practice can lead improvement in performance as sub-skills become automated, but it is also possible for increased practice to create conditions for restructuring, with attendant decrements in performance as learners reorganize their internal representational framework. In the second case, performance may follow a U-shaped curve, declining as more complex internal representations replace less complex ones, and increasing again as skill becomes expertise. Examples are drawn from first and second language research, and from research on expert systems. The cognitive approach is not seen as competitive to, but as complementary with, linguistic approaches to second language development.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "29ab491a518e4922",
      "text": "p. 114: For example, when engaged in conversation, speakers are using strategies for understanding and producing sentences, yet if asked to explain exactly how these strategies were being used, they would not be able to do so. Using a [[computer analogy]], we can say that speakers store [[Programs]] (strategies) in memory that enable them to understand and produce language. They can execute these programs when they wish to do so, but are not able to examine and report the details of the program."
